<paragraph blockId="21.[151,373,367,393]" box="[151,373,367,393]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[151,373,367,393]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="1">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,373,367,393]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[151,283,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispina">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,283,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Multispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,438,894]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Two species comprise the 
<taxonomicName box="[456,577,438,462]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispina">
<emphasis box="[456,577,438,462]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Multispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Group: 
<taxonomicName box="[685,840,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispina">
<emphasis box="[685,840,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. multispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[900,1055,438,463]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordispina">
<emphasis box="[900,1055,438,463]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. cordispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. These species are very unusual, having a spinose labrum and spinose elytra, and the elytra have only five series of punctures between the suture and the humeral umbo (
<figureCitation box="[372,512,510,534]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 21" captionStart-1="FIGURE 22" captionStartId-0="85.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionStartId-1="86.[151,250,1650,1673]" captionTargetBox-0="[253,1331,193,1626]" captionTargetBox-1="[305,1294,233,1606]" captionTargetId-0="figure@85.[253,1334,193,1629]" captionTargetId-1="figure@86.[270,1317,193,1629]" captionTargetPageId-0="85" captionTargetPageId-1="86" captionText-0="FIGURE 21. Hydraena multispina, holotype, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." captionText-1="FIGURE 22. Hydraena cordispina, holotype female, dorsal and lateral habitus, and venter." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1050084/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1050086/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Figs. 
<number box="[436,512,510,534]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="21.5" valueMax="22.0" valueMin="21.0">21–22</number>
</figureCitation>
). The coxae are rather widely separated by P 
<number box="[1023,1033,510,534]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="1.0">1</number>
and P 
<number box="[1107,1122,510,534]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="2.0">2</number>
, and the plaques are unusually shaped. The genae are carinate laterally. The aedeagus of 
<taxonomicName box="[845,998,547,571]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispina">
<emphasis box="[845,998,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. multispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is also very unusual (
<figureCitation box="[1242,1325,546,570]" captionStart="FIGURES 41 – 43" captionStartId="101.[151,264,1613,1636]" captionText="FIGURES 41 – 43. Aedeagi of holotypes." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[1294,1325,546,570]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="41.0">41</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,438,894]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Only females are known for 
<taxonomicName box="[524,679,582,607]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordispina">
<emphasis box="[524,679,582,607]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. cordispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; it is possible that this species is parthenogenetic (
<specimenCount box="[1252,1406,582,606]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="generic">
<number box="[1252,1281,582,606]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="20.0">20</number>
specimens
</specimenCount>
in 
<typeStatus box="[151,199,619,643]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
series, all female). The female gonocoxite in both species is &quot;divided&quot;, having a weakly sclerotized midlongitudinal area (
<figureCitation box="[303,404,654,678]" captionStart="FIGURES 148 – 150" captionStartId="176.[151,264,1581,1604]" captionTargetBox="[237,1360,212,1541]" captionTargetId="figure@176.[226,1360,193,1560]" captionTargetPageId="176" captionText="FIGURES 148 – 150. Female terminal abdominal segments of Hydraena species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050223/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[358,404,654,678]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="150.0">150</number>
</figureCitation>
). The spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[638,802,654,678]" captionStart="FIGURES 155 – 159" captionStartId="178.[151,264,1608,1631]" captionText="FIGURES 155 – 159. Spermathecae of Hydraena species." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Figs. 
<number box="[704,802,654,678]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="158.5" valueMax="159.0" valueMin="158.0">158–159</number>
</figureCitation>
) is more similar to that of members of the 
<emphasis box="[1311,1386,654,678]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Leechi</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[151,303,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Marginicollis</emphasis>
Groups than to that of the 
<taxonomicName box="[605,729,692,715]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paeminosa">
<emphasis box="[605,729,692,715]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Paeminosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[784,879,691,714]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="82" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvosa">
<emphasis box="[784,879,691,714]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Curvosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Groups. In 
<taxonomicName box="[1013,1167,691,715]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordispina">
<emphasis box="[1013,1167,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. cordispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the proximal end of the spermatheca, where the duct joins, is very constricted, and may be closed (
<figureCitation box="[987,1085,726,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 155 – 159" captionStartId="178.[151,264,1608,1631]" captionText="FIGURES 155 – 159. Spermathecae of Hydraena species." pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[1039,1085,726,750]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="159.0">159</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,438,894]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<taxonomicName box="[199,352,763,787]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cordispina">
<emphasis box="[199,352,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. cordispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected from leaf litter, and is probably humicolous. The microhabitat of 
<taxonomicName box="[1256,1409,763,787]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="multispina">
<emphasis box="[1256,1409,763,787]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">H. multispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not known, but characters of the female abdomen, specifically the patch of setae on each side of the fifth ventrite (
<figureCitation box="[159,256,834,858]" captionStart="FIGURES 148 – 150" captionStartId="176.[151,264,1581,1604]" captionTargetBox="[237,1360,212,1541]" captionTargetId="figure@176.[226,1360,193,1560]" captionTargetPageId="176" captionText="FIGURES 148 – 150. Female terminal abdominal segments of Hydraena species." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1050223/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Fig. 
<number box="[211,256,834,858]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" value="150.0">150</number>
</figureCitation>
), suggest less than fully aquatic habits (in fully aquatic 
<taxonomicName box="[877,989,835,859]" class="Insecta" family="Hydraenidae" genus="Hydraena" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[877,989,835,859]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Hydraena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these setae are in a transverse band that forms the posterior border of the ventral respiratory bubble).
</paragraph>
